# module namespace

Renders a namespace scope declaration as an XML context wrapper with an injected language-native namespacing instruction. Unlike app, lib, and module, the compiler does not emit the author's body verbatim — it prepends a namespacing mandate and appends a cross-boundary symbol-leakage prohibition, producing a single combined instruction inside the wrapper.

# entity Output

```markdown
<system_context type="NAMESPACE"{{#name}} name="{{name}}"{{/name}}>

{{#name}}All code in this scope belongs to the `{{name}}` namespace — emit it under the target language's namespacing construct (package, namespace, or module path) with this as the qualified name and import root.{{/name}}{{^name}}All code in this scope belongs to a dedicated namespace — emit it under the target language's namespacing construct with this as the import root.{{/name}} {{body}} Keep cross-namespace references explicit and do not leak symbols across this boundary.

</system_context>
```

# rule

- name is optional. A named namespace uses its name as the qualified name and import root; a nameless namespace uses the dedicated namespace wording from the documented template.
- {{^name}}...{{/name}} is an inverse conditional included only when name is empty.
- The compiler injects the namespacing mandate as a prefix and the symbol-leakage prohibition as a suffix — the author's body text is placed between them, not before or after the wrapper.
- Single-brace variable references in the body are resolved before this template executes.
- The closing `</system_context>` tag must always be present on its own line with a blank line before it.
